x="0 0 24 24" role="presentation"><g stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><path class="RatingStar__fill" d="M12.4770229,1.34326985 L15.0891563,9.1315756 L23.4968842,9.1315756 C23.7747474,9.1315756 24,9.35682823 24,9.63469143 C24,9.79809886 23.9206399,9.95132779 23.7871766,10.0456121 L16.9959586,14.8432273 L19.5982827,22.6117477 C19.6865419,22.8752212 19.5445026,23.1603569 19.2810291,23.2486161 C19.1293386,23.2994298 18.9625235,23.2750752 18.8316924,23.1830139 L12.0000207,18.3758025 L5.1685337,23.1876292 C4.94136559,23.3476374 4.62749722,23.2931935 4.46748907,23.0660254 C4.37533831,22.9351963 4.35092131,22.7683321 4.4017231,22.616585 L7.00408269,14.8432273 L0.212864685,10.0456121 C-0.0140805533,9.88528803 -0.0680876559,9.57134421 0.0922364448,9.34439897 C0.186520784,9.21093568 0.339749724,9.1315756 0.503157148,9.1315756 L8.910885,9.1315756 L11.5230185,1.34326985 C11.6113744,1.0798288 11.8965622,0.937894292 12.1600033,1.02625024 C12.3095218,1.07639751 12.4268756,1.19375135 12.4770229,1.34326985 Z"></path></g></svg></span></span></div><span class="Text Text__body3"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4152759293">Edited <!-- -->January 4, 2022</a></span></section><section class="ReviewText"><section class="ReviewText__content"><div class="TruncatedText"><div class="TruncatedText__text TruncatedText__text--5" data-testid="contentContainer"><div><span class="Formatted">Wow. I just finished this novel and I'm still feeling the power of the emotions it evokes. What an incredibly moving, intimate portrait of the lives of one family during the siege of Leningrad. It's like nothing I've ever read. The writing is so incredibly good - descriptive and detailed yet poetic and empathic. The message of this novel is that the human spirit can rise above the worst situations and deprivations. This book chronicles both. This story is told through the voice of Anna, a 22 year old woman who is taking care of her ailing father and her 5 year old brother, Kolya. Two other people share their apartment - a friend of the father's and a young doctor, Anna's first love. <br /><br /><input type="checkbox" class="spoiler__control" aria-label="The following text has been marked spoiler. Toggle checkbox to reveal or hide." onchange="this.labels[0].setAttribute('aria-hidden', !this.checked);" id="516fae32-b23e-4f1a-aa08-7309f3211ed5" /><label aria-hidden="true" class="spoiler" for="516fae32-b23e-4f1a-aa08-7309f3211ed5">The story starts before the siege, introducing the characters during beautiful summer days and nights in a dacha in the country. Once Germany invades and a food warehouse is blown up food becomes more and more scarce, winter sets in and temperatures drop. Scenes of Kolya crying for food because he doesn't understand why he can't eat when he's hungry are some of the most poignant in the book. But many other scenes rival those for poignancy. Anna is the "bread winner" in the family. Despite her severe weakness and hunger, she leaves her freezing apartment every morning and treks through the freezing snow (temperatures as low as -20), to pick up her family's smaller and smaller ration of "bread." During these agonizingly difficult trips she meets friends who are just as hungry, weak and cold as she. They are struggling to survive, just like Anna, but also like Anna, they are generous and compassionate. In one scene, Anna gives a neighbor the last of her sugar because her baby will die without it. The reader knows that Kolya is hungry and Anna gives away the sugar despite that and despite her "step mom" telling her that she needs to be selfish and think only of her own family. But in other scenes friends give Anna honey and wood. Her generosity is reciprocated and these are amazing windfalls which could make the difference between life and death for Anna and her family. I don't want to make it seem like this story is unrealistic about human nature. There are enough scenes which show the more selfish side and the baser instincts for self-preservation. But the author clearly focuses more on how generosity, love and compassion are not squelched by shared extremity, but are, perhaps, made stronger by it. </label><br /><br />I absolutely fell in love with Anna. By the half way point I couldn't stop reading. I didn't want to leave Anna for one moment. She and her family became real to me. I felt so sad and bereft after turning the last page. I will start the sequel immediately. </span></div></div></div></section></section><section class="ReviewCard__tags"><ul class="CollapsableList"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/2967061?shelf=2021" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">2021</span></a> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/2967061?shelf=favorites" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">favorites</span></a> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/2967061?shelf=historical-fiction" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">historical-fiction</span></a> <div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small" aria-label="Show all items in the list"><span class="Button__labelItem">...more</span></button></div></ul></section><footer class="SocialFooter"><div data-testid="stats" class="SocialFooter__statsContainer"><div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--inline Button--small Button--subdued"><span class="Button__labelItem">53 likes</span></button></div><div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--inline Button--small Button--subdued"><span class="Button__labelItem">48 comments</span></button></div></div><div data-testid="actions"><div class="SocialFooter__action"><div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem"><i class="Icon LikeIcon"><svg viewBox="0